{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491082","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491082"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:31:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:31:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"827"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"827","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/827"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.27,0.1,0.07,0.03,0.53]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"827"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103186"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"827","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/827"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"827"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85623"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1181"},{"type":"tags","id":"1432"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"8088"},{"type":"tags","id":"8218"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"728"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12376"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30011"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30138"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30139"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36559"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42162"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44484"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45057"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103186","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103186"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 46-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of a painless swelling in her neck. She has no symptoms suggestive of thyroid under or over-activity. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Physical examination reveals a 3 cm diameter soft, smooth swelling in the right lobe of the thyroid. The left thyroid lobe is not palpable. Her voice is normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following investigations will be most appropriate in determining the need for surgery?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ultrasound neck","Core biopsy","Thyroid scintigraphy","Sestamibi scan","Fine needle aspiration cytology"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical features are suggestive of a thyroid nodule without overt signs of malignancy or thyroid dysfunction. When evaluating thyroid nodules, the key question is whether surgery is required, which primarily depends on the risk of malignancy. \u003Cstrong\u003EFine needle aspiration cytology\u003C/strong\u003E is the gold standard investigation for determining this risk in nodules larger than 1 cm. It provides the most accurate information about the cellular characteristics of the nodule and is the investigation that most reliably guides surgical decision-making. The procedure is typically performed under ultrasound guidance, which also allows examination of the rest of the gland.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUltrasound neck\u003C/strong\u003E is an excellent initial imaging modality for thyroid nodules and can characterise features that suggest increased risk of malignancy (such as microcalcifications, hypoechogenicity, irregular margins, and increased vascularity - contribute to the TIRADS score). However, while ultrasound can stratify risk and guide biopsy as required, it cannot provide definitive cytological information needed to determine the need for surgery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECore biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E is more invasive than fine needle aspiration and is generally reserved for cases where FNA results are non-diagnostic or indeterminate. It is not the first-line investigation (and therefore not the most appropriate in this case) for determining the need for surgery in a typical thyroid nodule case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThyroid scintigraphy\u003C/strong\u003E (radionuclide scan) is primarily useful for determining the functional status of thyroid nodules. It can identify hyperfunctioning (\u0022hot\u0022) nodules, which are rarely malignant, versus hypofunctioning (\u0022cold\u0022) nodules, which have a higher risk of malignancy. However, this investigation is most valuable when there are clinical or biochemical features of hyper or hypothyroidism, which are absent in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESestamibi scan\u003C/strong\u003E is not routinely used in the evaluation of thyroid nodules. It is more commonly employed in the assessment of parathyroid adenomas and hyperplasia. It has limited utility in determining the need for thyroid surgery in this clinical scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn addition to the investigations discussed, thyroid function tests should be performed in all patients with thyroid nodules to exclude hypo- or hyperthyroidism, though these results would not typically be the primary determinant of the need for surgery.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Fine needle aspiration cytology is the most accurate investigation for determining the need for surgery in thyroid nodules larger than 1 cm.","Ultrasound examination is useful for characterising thyroid nodules and determining which require further assessment, but cytology provides more definitive information about malignancy risk.","Thyroid function tests should be performed in all patients with thyroid nodules to exclude hypo- or hyperthyroidism."],"references":["Bomeli SR, LeBeau SO, Ferris RL. Evaluation of a thyroid nodule. Otolaryngol Clin North Am 2010; 43:229-38. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/20510711/","Grani G, Sponziello M, Filetti S, et al. Thyroid nodules: diagnosis and management. Nat Rev Endocrinol. 2024. 20:715\u2013728. Available at: https://www.nature.com/articles/s41574-024-01025-4","Wong R, Farrell SG, Grossmann M. Thyroid nodules: diagnosis and management. Med J Aust. 2018. 16;209(2):92-98. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29996756/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85623"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"827"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85623","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/85623"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-20T14:24:32+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-15T16:21:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"827"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103186"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount